'''''My Kind of Christmas''''' is the third [[studio album]] and first [[Christmas album]] by American recording artist [[Christina Aguilera]]. It was released on October 24, 2000, by [[RCA Records]]. The album was recorded from late-1999 to late-2000, while Aguilera was [[Christina Aguilera in Concert|touring]] to promote her first two studio albums: ''[[Christina Aguilera (album)|Christina Aguilera]]'' (1999) and ''[[Mi Reflejo]]'' (2000). ''My Kind of Christmas'' contains cover versions of Christmas standards, such as "[[Have Yourself a Merry Little Christmas]]" and "[[Angels We Have Heard on High]]", as well as several original recordings, which incorporate [[dance-pop]] elements. The album was produced by [[Ron Fair]], [[The Matrix (production team)|The Matrix]], [[Robbie Buchanan]], [[Barry Harris (Canadian musician)|Barry Harris]] and [[Chris Cox (DJ)|Chris Cox]].

''My Kind of Christmas'' received generally mixed to negative reviews from [[Music journalism|music critics]], who criticized its musical style, as well as Aguilera's vocal delivery. The album peaked at number 28 on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and was certified [[RIAA certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), having sold 991,000 copies there. Aguilera appeared on several television shows, such as ''[[The Early Show]]'' and ''[[The David Letterman Show]]'', to promote the album, and also performed a special concert for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], which was released on DVD in June 2001, as ''[[My Reflection]]''.

==Background and composition==
{{Listen|filename=The Christmas Song (Holiday Remix).ogg|title="The Christmas Song (Holiday Remix)"|description=A 25-second sample of "[[The Christmas Song|The Christmas Song (Holiday Remix)]]", a [[dance music|dance]] number which is set to "a kicking dance beat."<ref name="review"/>|format=Ogg|pos=left}}
Aguilera achieved her early success following the release of the two first [[studio albums]], ''[[Christina Aguilera (album)|Christina Aguilera]]'' in 1999 and ''[[Mi Reflejo]]'' in mid-2000, both of which were certified [[RIAA certification|multi-platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref name="riaa"/> ''My Kind of Christmas'' was recorded from late-1999 to mid-2000, when Aguilera was [[Christina Aguilera in Concert|touring]] to support her two debut recordings.<ref name="notes">{{cite AV media notes|others=Christina Aguilera|title=My Kind of Christmas|year=2000|type=liner notes|publisher= [[RCA Records]]|location=United States}}</ref> Originally, Aguilera's idol [[Etta James]] was planned to be included as a featured performer on the track "Merry Christmas, Baby".<ref name="ew">{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,90405,00.html|title=My Kind of Christmas Review|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|first=Chris|last=Willman|date=December 4, 2000|accessdate=November 26, 2013}}</ref> However the idea was later canceled, and [[Dr. John]] was chosen as her replacement afterwards.<ref name="notes"/> It is a [[Christmas music|Christmas]] and [[dance-pop]] album,<ref name="AllMusic">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/my-kind-of-christmas-mw0000100386 |title=My Kind of Christmas by Christina Aguilera on AllMusic |deadurl=no |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6AeKy4Z9e |archivedate=September 12, 2012 |accessdate=September 13, 2012|publisher=[[AllMusic]]. All Media Network|first=Stephen|last=Erlewine}}</ref> which contains mainly [[cover version]]s of Christmas standards and several new tracks, including "Christmas Time", "This Year" and "Xtina's Xmas".<ref name="notes"/> "[[Have Yourself a Merry Little Christmas]]" and "[[Merry Christmas, Baby]]" are the two "soulful" [[ballad]]s from the album, backed by a 70-piece orchestra. "Christmas Time" and the "[[Diane Warren]]-written" track "These Are the Special Times", meanwhile, are the two "painful" tracks. "Christmas Time" and "This Year" are the two "[[hip hop music|hip hop]] influenced" pop tracks. "[[The Christmas Song|The Christmas Song (Holiday Remix)]]" was remade as a [[dance music|dance]]-styled number, which is set to "a kicking dance beat".<ref name="review"/> "The Christmas Song (Chestnut Roasting on an Open Fire)" released as a single in late-1999 was included in the album.<ref name="AllMusic"/>

==Promotion==
The album was released on October 24, 2000, by [[RCA Records]] as Aguilera's third [[studio album]] in the United States, following her two first albums ''[[Christina Aguilera (album)|Christina Aguilera]]'' (1999) and ''[[Mi Reflejo]]'' (2000).<ref name=AllMusic/> It was released as two formats: [[Compact disc|CD]] and [[cassette tape|cassette]].<ref name=AllMusic/> In order to promote the album, Aguilera promoted the album on a number of shows, including ''[[The Rosie O'Donnell Show]]'', ''[[The Early Show]]'', and ''[[David Letterman Show]]''.<ref name="single">{{harvnb|Dominguez|2003|page=175}}</ref> On December 10, 2000, Aguilera performed "The Christmas Song", "[[Genie in a Bottle]]" and "[[What a Girl Wants (Christina Aguilera song)|What a Girl Wants]]" during a concert at [[Franklin High School (Franklin, Wisconsin)|Franklin High]] in [[Milwaukee]], being watched by 1,300 students.<ref>{{harvnb|Dominguez|2003|page=90}}</ref> She also performed during an [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] special concert later in December; the set list included songs from her three first studio albums, including a song from ''My Kind of Christmas'', "Have Yourself A Little Merry Christmas".<ref name=xmas>{{harvnb|Dominguez|2003|page=181}}</ref> There, she performed the track with [[Brian McKnight]].<ref name=xmas/> The concert was filmed and released as a [[DVD]] entitled ''[[My Reflection]]'' (2001).<ref name=xmas/>

==Reception==
{{Album reviews
|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]<ref name=AllMusic/>
|rev1score = {{rating|3|5}}
|rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''<ref name=ew/>
|rev2score = (C)
|rev3 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''<ref name="rs"/>
|rev3score = (negative)
|rev4 = ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]''<ref name="review"/>
|rev4score = (mixed)
}}
The album garnered mixed reviews from [[music journalism|music critics]], some of them criticized her vocals. [[AllMusic]] editor [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] wrote that "none of the new songs are knockouts" but "it does suggest that she may not be a mere one-album wonder".<ref name="AllMusic"/> Chris Willman from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' thought that "Aguilera oversings so wildly that there wouldn't have been enough oxygen in the booth to sustain another life form".<ref name=ew/> Jaan Uhelszki from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' criticized the album as being "chilly, forced and overdone",<ref name="rs">{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/shoddy-and-nice-holiday-releases-20001213|title=Shoddy and Nice Holiday Releases|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Wenner Media]]|date=December 13, 2000|accessdate=November 27, 2013}}</ref> while ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' was not impressed toward Aguilera's vocal ability on the album, giving it a mixed review.<ref name="review">{{harvnb|Dominguez|2003|page=180}}</ref>

''My Kind of Christmas'' debuted at number 38 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/christinaaguilera/5054|title=Snow Way!|date=November 3, 2000|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|accessdate=November 27, 2013}}</ref> and later climbed to number 28, its peak.<ref name="bb"/> It eventually peaked atop the ''Billboard'' Holiday Albums. Due to its chart success, the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) certified the album [[RIAA certification|platinum]],<ref name=riaa/> having sold more than 991,000 copies in the country.<ref name=sales/> "The Christmas Song" became Aguilera's third top-twenty hit on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, peaking at number 18 on the chart.<ref name=bb/> It also charted at number 22 in Canada.<ref name=bb/> By the end of 2000, ''My Kind of Christmas'' was the second best selling holiday album of the year, making Aguilera one of the four female artists to have the second best selling holiday album of a calendar year, among [[Amy Grant]] (1992), [[Mariah Carey]] (1994), and [[Jackie Evancho]] (2010).<ref name="yearend"/> In November 2013, the album entered the International Albums chart in [[Gaon Chart|South Korea]] at number 37.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/digital_chart/album.php?nationGbn=E&current_year=&current_month=11&current_week=47&chart_Time=week |title=GAON ALBUM CHART |language=Korean |publisher=Gaon Chart |archiveurl=http://archive.is/6pN03 |archivedate=November 4, 2013 |accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref>

